<header>
  <h1>Henry George, the Prophet Rejected by His Own but Embraced in the East</h1>
</header>

<div class="epigraph">"The equal right of all men to the use of land is as clear as their equal right to breathe the air &mdash; it is a right proclaimed by the fact of their existence." &mdash; Henry George, <em>Progress and Poverty</em> (1879)</div>

<p>In 1879, a San Francisco printer published a book that would ignite land-reform movements from London to Tokyo. Henry George's <em>Progress and Poverty</em> sold millions, outpacing every book except the Bible in the 1890s. He ran for mayor of New York twice, nearly winning. Winston Churchill quoted him in Parliament. Yet in the West, George's core proposal &mdash; a single tax on land values &mdash; was debated, diluted, and ultimately discarded.</p>

<p>Half a world away, in the cramped harbours of Hong Kong and the reclaimed swamps of Singapore, his ideas became state policy. Today, these cities stand as the world's most successful urban economies, funding world-class infrastructure with land rents while keeping income taxes near zero. The irony is complete: the American prophet, spurned at home, found his promised land in the East.</p>

<h2>The Georgist Gospel: Land Is Not Capital</h2>
<p>George's insight was simple yet revolutionary:</p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Land value is created by community, not owners.</strong> A plot near a new subway station soars in price &mdash; yet the owner did nothing.</li>
  <li><strong>Tax the unearned increment (land rent) at 100%.</strong> Return it to the public as schools, transit, hospitals.</li>
  <li><strong>Untax everything else</strong> &mdash; wages, buildings, trade. Reward work, not speculation.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Hong Kong: The Single Tax in Practice (1898&ndash;1997)</h2>
<p>When Britain seized Hong Kong Island in 1841, it auctioned land as freehold to raise quick cash. Speculation exploded. By 1890, prime lots changed hands for fortunes while squatters lived in shacks.</p>
<p>Colonial reformers, fresh from London debates, cited <em>Progress and Poverty</em> in official reports. In 1898, Governor Henry Blake converted all new land grants to 99-year leases. The government became universal landlord: upfront premiums captured land value at auction, annual ground rent skimmed ongoing increases, and buildings went untaxed.</p>
<blockquote>Official Ordinance (1905): "The system&hellip; is in accordance with the principles advocated by Henry George."</blockquote>
<p>By the 1960s, land revenue funded 50&ndash;60% of the budget. No income tax until 1947 &mdash; and then only 15%. Refugees poured in; public housing rose. Hong Kong became the freest economy on Earth (Heritage Foundation, 1995&ndash;2020), built on Georgist foundations.</p>

<h2>Singapore: From Slums to Skyscrapers on Land Rents</h2>
<p>In 1965, Singapore was expelled from Malaysia. Unemployment: 14%. Slums: 300,000 squatters. Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew had studied Sun Yat-sen, China's revolutionary leader and Henry George's most famous disciple.</p>
<blockquote>"The teachings of Henry George will be the basis of our program of reform." &mdash; Sun Yat-sen, 1912</blockquote>

<div class="table-wrapper">
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Singapore Policy</th><th>Georgist Logic</th><th>Outcome</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Land Acquisition Act (1966)</td><td>Buy land at 1973 values; no windfalls from public works</td><td>State land: 90% by 1985</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Development Charges</td><td>70&ndash;100% tax on rezoning uplift</td><td>Funds HDB flats for 82% of citizens</td></tr>
      <tr><td>99-Year Leases</td><td>Value reverts to state at expiry</td><td>Prevents dynastic landlordism</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

<blockquote>Lee Kuan Yew (1998): "We followed the Henry George theorem: the increment in land value due to public investment should accrue to the state."</blockquote>
<p>Result? Poverty fell from 25% to under 1%. GDP per capita: $1,240 (1965) &rarr; $82,800 (2025). Income tax: 0&ndash;22%. Land revenue: 20&ndash;30% of budget.</p>

<h2>The East Embraced What the West Rejected</h2>
<div class="table-wrapper">
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Region</th><th>Georgist Outcome</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>United States</td><td>Single-tax colonies failed. Property tax includes buildings. Land speculation fuels housing crises.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>United Kingdom</td><td>Lloyd George's 1909 "People's Budget" LVT defeated by House of Lords. Today: council tax hits improvements.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hong Kong &amp; Singapore</td><td>Zero landlord class. Rents fund subways, airports, universities. Homeownership: 90%+ in Singapore.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>

<p>Why the divergence? Three factors: a colonial clean slate that was never privatized en masse; existential urgency in tiny, defenseless cities that couldn't afford speculative bubbles; and post-colonial leaders who faced no entrenched aristocracy to compensate.</p>

<h2>The Prophet's Revenge: A Global Housing Crisis</h2>
<p>In 2025, the West wakes up to Georgist ghosts. San Francisco median home: $1.4M. London average flat: &pound;700,000. New York has vacant lots held for decades, taxed at 0.03% of value. Meanwhile, Singapore builds 20,000 public flats yearly &mdash; subsidized by land rents.</p>
<blockquote>Paul Krugman (2023): "We should have listened to Henry George. Land value tax is the closest thing to a free lunch in economics."</blockquote>

<h2>Epilogue: The Return of the Single Tax?</h2>
<p>Estonia, Denmark, and Pittsburgh use split-rate taxation (higher on land, lower on buildings). Scotland pilots LVT in 2026. Even California debates public land leasing for new towns.</p>
<p>Henry George died in 1897, mid-campaign, mourned by 100,000 in New York. His ideas were buried in the West &mdash; only to rise in the East, where two small islands proved: <strong>Tax land, not people. Build cities, not fortunes.</strong></p>
<p>The prophet was rejected by his own. But in the East, he became the architect of miracles.</p>

